<br>
In terms of complexity Terris Thule is still way ahead of anything outside of PoP and maybe Emp/Seru/VexThall, which I have not experienced.    If you are used to a mobs like Avatar of War, Tunare, or Vyemm, chances are really good that your first try on Terris will go like this:<br>
<br>
Hey look at those Gargoyle statue things, they'll probably add during the fight.  Tanks and healers be ready to tank mez.<br>
<br>
So you set up and pull, whatever, probably patting yourself on the back for figuring that part out.  The battle starts, everything seems to be going well TT is going down you are staying up.<br>
<br>
Then At 75% holy sh!t what is going on why are people dying?<br>
<br>
IF you manage to adjust your strategy fast enough to deal with the first surprise, the second one will totally own you if you don't know it is coming(well unless you've been farming VT for months and are overpowered for the encounter).<br>
<br>
You show up at your bind point trying to figure out what exactly you just saw, because it was unlike anything you've ever seen before.  It's not like wiping out to Vindicator for the first time, where it's pretty obvious that this guy just has a massive damage output.  It's not even like wiping out to Zlexak, where it's not too hard to see that you just got destroyed by a rather nasty AE.  Sure, you'll probably need to try a couple different strategies for each of those guys into you find something that works..  But they are still fairly one dimensional mobs.  For Terris, you'll probably wipe at least once to just get a hint of what you are up against, and probably several more times to figure out how best to handle it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Like Awer said, if you don't want to read spoilers, don't. If you do, go for it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This doesn't generally work.  It just doesn't feel right to ignore available information.  When you are challenged, naturally you try your best and use all the resources you can.  Reading spoiler sites is hard to rationalize as cheating in a game as social as Everquest.  So for many, igoring spoilers simply isn't an option.<br>
<br>
That said, I have no problem with anyone sharing spoilers among friends.  If you want to send cross server tells and stuff to discuss whatever fighst you want go nuts.  Your friends should know whether you care about spoilers.<br>
<br>
A public space like this is different, though.  While you may post here answering Svenuce, you're also telling everyone who reads the board and is interested.<br>
